Our safe and convenient location features many restaurants and grocery stores within walking distance, along with easy parking and public transportation to downtown. Enjoy the beach or unwind in our lovely backyard with a cup of coffee. Weâ€™re confident youâ€™ll have a great stay with us!!
neighborhood_overview: The Sunset District is the largest neighborhood within the city and county of San Francisco, and with a population of over 85,000. It is also the most populous. Golden Gate Park forms the neighborhood's northern border, and the Pacific Ocean (or, more specifically, the long, flat strand of beach known as Ocean Beach) forms its western border. A section of the Sunset District towards its southeastern end is known as the Parkside neighborhood. Prior to the residential and commercial development of the Sunset District, much of the area was covered by sand dunes and was originally referred to by 19th century San Franciscans as the "Outside Lands."

neighborhood_overview:
Bernal Heights is an urban village built onto a hill. As a result, it is one of the more magical neighborhoods of San Francisco. Walks in Bernal Heights include numerous stairway streets, hidden mini-parks and gardens, panoramic views of the city and the bay, and frequent opportunities for refreshment breaks at corner stores, cafes, restaurants and bars. This is an urban hikerâ€™s paradise! To really get the full neighborhood experience youâ€™ll have to take it off-roading since some areas are only accessible by foot, but even if you stick to streets youâ€™ll still fall in love with the whimsical charm around every corner.

There are numerous coffee shops in the immediate vicinity, and the famous Mitchell's ice cream is just two blocks away. If you are craving a San Francisco burrito, Taqueria Can-Cun is just around the corner. Some other noteworthy restaurants just a stone's throw away are Baby Blues BBQ, The Front Porch (soul food), Blue Plate (new-style American), ICHI+NI (s

neighborhood_overview:
Neighborhood: MISSION The Mission is perhaps the trendiest neighborhood of San Francisco, and Mission Concourse is located in perhaps the trendiest part of the Mission. A mix of hipsters, tech employees, and families who have lived in the area for a generation, this area gives you a friendly view to a true cross-section of the city. Within a block or two you will find super-hot bars like Trick Bar, great artisan restaurants like Salumeria, and legendary San Francisco eateries like Flour and Water.

Of course you are in the Mission so you will find a large selection of restaurants serving authentic Mexican, Ecuadorian, Guatemalan and other ethnic foods at low prices. We like Mis Antojitos on 22nd and Bryan, or even Dona Teresa which is two doors down, both owned by neighbors.

There is a fantastic convenience store steps away on the corner stocking gourmet foods, drinks (including beer, wine, and liquor), ice and other necessary and not-so-necessary items. Across the
host_about:
I love my family, without them nothing would be
the same!
San Francisco is such an amazing city surrounded by history, unique culture
and special events throughout the whole year, and I want to make sure my
guests enjoy their stay as much as possible!
My favorite places in the world are San Francisco, Menorca, Barcelona and a place I haven't been yet.

name: (#3) 3BR 1Ba Renovated Flat in the heart of SoMA
description:
Extraordinary location close to everything. 1.5 blocks to BART/Muni. This is Unit #3 in a 5-unit 1920's Edwardian building on a quiet street in SoMa, fully remodeled in 2018. It has an open kitchen/living area with eating bar. Each bedroom has a large closet & a work desk. Lease can be 1 month to 1 year.

Perfect for a group that is new to the area and needs a place to land with no hassle, or doesn't have their own furniture. An easy way get to know the City. Good wifi for working from home.
neighborhood_overview: One hundred year ago, SoMa (or South-of-Market) was built with wide boulevards that held warehouses or factories on the corners and perimeter of each block. Nowadays, these are converted apartments or loft buildings.  The interior of the large blocks contained smaller street and were quiet "Residential Enclaves" of two- and three- story Edwardian flats, built with the last of the redwood from nearby forests in the 1910s and 20s. These enclaves today are hidden clusters of refurbished older homes that feel neighborly and almost private.  It's a highly walkable neighborhood with many bars, restaurants and clubs along the main roads, yet quiet and residential inside. Mid-SoMa, where we are, is very close to City Hall, a 1.5 block walk to Civic Center BART and Muni (which can get you anywhere in the region), easily walkable to Moscone Convention Center and the Financial and Hotel districts. Shopping at Union Square is about four blocks away!
host_about: I have lived in San Francisco for 30 years with a brief stint in Denver . My parents are in Asheville and it has become my second home over the last few years. I'm now here more than half-time. I am the co-founder the AIDS Memorial Quilt, which started on my back porch in 1987 (Younger people have no clue what this is, but a online search should help...) I've been running AIDS or LGBT organizations my whole adult life and enjoy the community-building aspect of what I do.  I recently retired as executive director of AIDS Emergency Fund and Breast Cancer Emergency Fund, two related non-profits that help low income people pay their basic living costs while disabled or going through surgery, chemo or radiation.  I am grateful to the many hosts on Airbnb who have opened their homes to me when I travel, and I was inspired by them top remodel this farmhouse for your enjoyment.

name: Adorable private "in-law" for two
description: Private cheery "in-law" apartment in our home of 40 years. WELL VENTILATED and SUPER CLEAN!  Close to the beach, Golden Gate Park, Stern Grove, Landâ€™s End, restaurants & bars, streetcar line and freeways.  Also close to San Francisco State University and the University of California San Francisco.  Perfect SF neighborhood with many amenities within walking distance.
neighborhood_overview:
This neighborhood is the Sunset/Parkside District, which is on the western side of San Francisco. There is easy access to many amenities and to public transportation. The streetcar stop is one block away. The streetcar (L Taraval line) will get you downtown in about 20 minutes. If you have a car, parking is free but can get tricky in the evenings. (Sometimes we can save spots for our guests.) The freeways are close also, if you need them. We are within a couple miles of wonderful parts of San Francisco, including Ocean Beach, Stern Grove, Landâ€™s End and Golden Gate Park. There are bars and restaurants within easy walking distance. There is also a laundromat and a 24 hour convenience store on the corner. This is a very safe neighborhood.

We have lived in this house for 40 years. Some neighbors on our block have been here even longer, which is highly unique in San Francisco.

We love to walk to the beach (slightly over a mile) and watch the sun set.
host_about:
Hi there.  We have been married and living in this house that we love for over 40 years.  Our daughter attended school in the neighborhood, and our next door neighbors on both sides have lived here even longer than we have. 

I moved to San Francisco in 1977; Charlie arrived in the 1960s. We still believe this is the best city in the world, despite its many difficult changes.

I am an outdoor person!  I roller skate all over town, and lead the weekly (world famous) San Francisco Friday Night Skate.  Charlie is an indoor person.  One of his favorite things to do is cook, and he's fabulous at it. 

We will totally respect whatever level of host/guest interaction you desire, and look forward to having you in our home!
Thanks for reading!

neighborhood_overview:
Located in the Outer Mission area in San Francisco. It is ethnically diverse and is burstling with families. Staying in a local neighborhood is less expensive and yet youâ€™re just minutes away from the trendy areas of San Francisco. The place is just Â½ mile to freeway access to South San Francisco, Daly City and the peninsular and the East Bay.

There are colorful murals around the neighborhoods. Casual Mexican and Asian food spots dot the streets, along with diners, corner stores, and ethnic markets.

Outer Mission borders Excelsior District which is home to the Excelsior Festival, an annual event celebrating its cultural diversity. It brings in about 5,000 people each year and has free music and entertainment. There is also Jerry Day, a celebration of the areaâ€™s most famous former resident, Jerry Garcia, lead singer of the Grateful Dead.

neighborhood_overview:
We are conveniently located in NoPa near everything.

NoPa is a tiny section carved out of the larger Western Addition neighborhood. Itâ€™s named after its location, the streets sitting *north of the panhandle* (the narrow eastern strip of Golden Gate Park). Itâ€™s a trendy area with popular, highly rated bars and restaurants along Divisadero Street, its eastern border, and rising costs because of its prime central location within the city. Youâ€™ll also find college students in the area, as the University of San Francisco makes up the neighborhoodâ€™s western border.

NoPa offers great little cafes and shops within 2 blocks and along the Divisadero corridor 4 blocks away. You can walk to Haight/Ashbury, Golden Gate Park, UCSF and Alamo Square and its famous painted ladies; the Castro, Mission, downtown, Union Square, Pac Heights and the Marina using public transportation.

neighborhood_overview:
The southern part of Outer Sunset neighborhood in San Francisco is a peaceful and quiet residential area located along the city's western coast. Known for its stunning ocean views and wide stretches of sandy beaches, it offers a laid-back vibe that is perfect for those seeking a relaxing getaway.

The neighborhood is home to an array of independent coffee shops, restaurants, and boutiques, as well as the popular Ocean Beach and SF Zoo. Visitors can enjoy scenic walks along the beach, and panoramic views of the Pacific Ocean, as well as some scenic hikes if they go North to Golden Gate Park. Overall, the Outer Sunset is a must-visit destination for anyone looking to experience the natural beauty and tranquility of San Francisco.

neighborhood_overview:
A serene well established neighborhood with views, lovely walks, close to FREEWAYS, restaurants, banks, stores, parks and 2 BLOCKS TO 2 BUS LINES. The people that live here, stay a lifetime. It is a "happening" area in that one can travel anywhere quickly --- within the city, North or South on Freeways 101 or 280 freeways to travel to the downtown area or to the Peninsula/Silicon Valley, or Marin areas --- and come home anytime day or night to beauty, safety and always to PLENTY of PARKING.


A LITTLE HISTORY
On Mt. Davidson, one of the famous 7 HILLS of San Francisco, lies this area named MONTEREY HEIGHTS. It is located, one block above St. Francis Wood, very close to the infamous WEST PORTAL. "West Portal" is derived from it being the "west" "port" "hole" of San Francisco, that refers to the tunnel at one end of West Portal that brings people from downtown to the west side of SF. The VIEWS from my home are of western SF all the way to the Pacific Ocean.

description:

neighborhood_overview: Geographically, I live in the Eureka Valley also known as the sun belt of San Francisco. If the fog burns off, it burns off first in our neighborhood. All public transportation comes to our neighborhood. You can walk to the Mission, Hayes Valley, the Castro and the Civic Center.
host_about:
I live  alone in my our art filled home in the Lower Haight â€” central to everything. I retired from working downtown in Union Square; it takes very little effort to get there, three stops on MUNI. Our public-transit system is everywhere and very close to the house (be it a MUNI, the N Judah â€” underground â€” or the street car on Market Street). Our closest surrounding neighborhoods are Hayes Valley, Duboce Triangle, The Castro (just underwent extensive renovations), the Upper Haight and Valencia Street in the Mission District. On Waller Street we're literally steps away from some of the best food, bars and shopping (not tourist spots). The Lower Haight was voted the number one neighborhood in San Francisco by the tech community. Most important, do not rent a large car or let the car agency upgrade you to a larger car. Parking is too difficult. The rental agency tries to unload larger cars by offering visitors an upgrade. Don't accept it. I allow my guests to park in the street in front of my garage providing there is enough room.

My home (pre earthquake Edwardian) has been with me for more than forty years, so you can ask me anything that you want to know about the Bay Area and I am  bound to point you in the right direction. What else... Ah, just feel free to be in touch. I look forward to having you around! I just concluded my ninth year as a host on Airbnb. I am continually told that my price is too low. I am OK with my fee. I really want my guests to have a great time when staying in my home. To paraphrase the clothing designer Tom Ford, " Surrounding yourself with beautiful objects, enhances the quality of your life". It is my  unofficial motto. 

After hosting many guests from many different places, I learned that it is important to understand that when you book my home you are also experiencing my life. I have friends that stop by. I occasionally have people for dinner. It is essential to understand that I am not a professional innkeeper. I am not running a bed and breakfast. I am an Airbnb host who accept guests to stay in my guest bedrooms. I want my guests to live like residents of San Francisco. My neighborhood is very popular. When you stay with me you are returning to your San Francisco home.

neighborhood_overview:
The Neighborhood

Our lovely Victorian is in one of the most desirable areas of San Francisco, along the edge of Pacific Heights and less than two blocks from Presidio Heights. Laurel Heights and historic Fillmore Street, in the Western Addition, are nearby.

These neighborhoods are home to some of San Francisco's best shopping, eating, and drinking establishments.

Fillmore Street has dozens of restaurants, clothing and furniture stores. And, of course, the legendary jazz district and the famed Fillmore Auditorium music venue, plus the Sundance Cinema movie complex.

A smaller, neighborhood movie theater is just two blocks from the flat, on Sacramento Street. There is an eclectic mix of shops and restaurants along Sacramento Street.

Popular restaurants just a short stroll from our home include Eliza's (Chinese), Bistro SF Grill (gourmet burgers), Curbside Cafe (French Bistro), Sift (dessert cafe) and Osteria (Northern Italian).

I am self-employed who works from home in the marketing and broadcast media. Alexandra is a manager in the travel and leisure industry here in San Francisco.  

We are all avid San Franciscans who are happy to share tips about the city that we love. We are friendly, and easy going folks who enjoy meeting travelers from all backgrounds & walks of life.  We aim to treat people with the same respect and hospitality that we hope to receive.   We enjoy making our home a place of welcome for all our friends and especially friends we haven't met yet...we hope we can welcome you here soon.

neighborhood_overview:
Located in San Francisco Crocker Amazon. Diverse community featuring commercial businesses, including a barber shop and a separate barber school, an optometrist, pizzerias, pharmacies, a hardware store, and a vegetable market. The area also features a growing number of restaurants and cafes, many featuring various types of Mexican and Latin American (particularly Salvadoran) cuisine.

Crocker-Amazon Park borders the neighborhood to the north. It has four playgrounds and recently renovated and lighted soccer and baseball fields. Adjacent to the east of Crocker-Amazon park is McLaren Park, San Francisco's third largest park after Golden Gate and the Presidio. It has a golf course, two lakes, jogging and hiking trails, a public pool, an old reservoir that is used as a dog swimming area, and the Jerry Garcia Amphitheater which houses concerts and festivals.

name: Peaceful Mid-Century Modern gem
description:
Inviting, lovingly cared for home, quiet and safe in desirable Portola neighborhood of San Francisco.
The home is very clean with great mid century modern finishes, beautiful hardwood floors, upstairs deck off the main bedroom looks over our private yard. Enter through the classic San Francisco breezeway entrance to your spacious flat.
A few blocks away is McLaren Park, Jerry Garcia Amphiteatre and vibrant San Bruno ave.. Easy freeway/ SFO access, short bike/bus/ drive to the Civic center.
neighborhood_overview:
Safe and walkable neighborhood, blocks away from the second largest park in San Francisco. McLaren park boasts a huge public city golf course with amazing views, locals love the park because it's quiet and not run over by tourists. Downtown Portola sports a great little downtown street (San Bruno Ave) which is a short walk with great local and ethnic food spots, coffee shops and local flavor. One of the sunniest areas in fog city.

Grocery Outlet is a 15 min walk ( mostly flat), and SFO is 10 min's by car, with several city bus lines a block away.

name: SF Home- Mins to the Beach, 20 Mins to Downtown SF
description: Sunny and Spacious 2 bedroom home in the Sunset  that's perfect for those coming to explore or work in SF! Walkable to both Ocean Beach and SF Zoo while only being a 10 min drive to Golden Gate Park, and a 20 min drive to either the Golden Gate Bridge or Downtown SF!
neighborhood_overview:
Our home in the Sunset neighborhood of SF and is perfectly situated to access the entire city using public transportation or walking.

We're close to Inner Sunset and Irving area, Golden Gate Park, and Dim Sum (Irving Street) are walking distance from the house.

Irving street is a bustling corridor of activity, especially weekends. There's so many good restaurants around the corner. Chinese, Thai, Vietnamese, Pakistani, Japanese, Middle Eastern, Taiwanese Boba or go to the local and good grocery store around the corner and cook a meal at home.

It's a quiet and safe neighborhood to wander around.

Easy access to both the Ocean Beach and Financial District/Downtown via the L Line Streetcar (45 mins to SoMa via public transit and 20 mins by car).

We're also only a mile from the beach and the Pacific Ocean.
host_about:
Greetings from Noelle and George!

We both grew up in the Bay Area and are college sweethearts having both majored in biological sciences. We chose to live and raise a family which includes our three children in San Francisco because of the beautiful landscape, amazing culture and diversity, priceless climate and lets not forget exploring this beautiful city through the iconic cable car rides.

As a family we enjoy spending most of our time outdoors which includes hiking in the Marin Headlands, breezy walks along Ocean Beach, as well as biking in Golden Gate Park to name a few. Camping is a major part of our summer routine in Lake Tahoe, Yosemite National Park, and Camp Mendocino. We also enjoy Lake Tahoe during the winter months for skiing and snowboarding. Noelle and I are also avid sports fans and LOVE attending San Francisco Giants, Oakland Athletics, Golden State Warriors, San Francisco Forty Niners, Oakland Raiders and San Jose Shark games with our children and friends. Our weekends are also consumed with youth sports as our children play on baseball, basketball, golf, and swimming teams.

 We are lucky enough to live in an area which embraces the arts and we are just a short stroll away from the many music festivals which San Francisco has to offer and a few of our favorite events to attend are the Blue Grass Festival and Outside Lands both in Golden Gate Park. 

San Francisco offers a variety of multi-cultural cuisine all within a short distance from each other whether it be a walk, drive or door step away. Some of our favorites include, fresh seafood, Pho, Mission-style burritos, Korean BBQ, Cioppino, or exploring our palates with tasting world renowned wine and cheese at the Ferry Building!

neighborhood_overview:
The home is located in the Oceanview neighborhood of San Francisco, California. This residential area is a mix of older homes and newer developments, with a diverse community of residents.

The neighborhood is conveniently located near public transportation, including the Muni light rail and multiple bus lines, providing easy access to downtown San Francisco and other parts of the city. The nearby Ocean Avenue commercial district offers a variety of shops, restaurants, and services, including a grocery store, pharmacy, and cafes.

There are also bus stops for FIVE separate SF Muni bus routes within three blocks of the house, which can take you to just about any point within the city.

The flat is the upper of two units in an historic cottage on Macondray Lane, a lovely lane which runs between Taylor and Jones streets. The Lane is vibrant green with abundant gardens and a brick and cobblestone walkway. Note: The Lane is walking only; no cars.

Commercial stretches along Polk and Hyde Streets on ones side of Russian Hill offer an assortment of trendy and old-school restaurants, bars and shops, while on the other side the bustling neighborhoods of North Beach and Chinatown are just a few blocks away. Guests can look down on Fisherman's Wharf and can walk there in less than 15 minutes.

neighborhood_overview:

15 min walk from Mission Dolores: At the corner of 16th and Dolores streets, overshadowed by an ornate basilica, sits a modest adobe chapel, one of the two original missions in San Francisco and the oldest standing building in the city. The inside of the chapel (note the ceiling patterned after Costonoan basket weaving -- Costonoans were the native inhabitants of the area) and the mission's cemetery and gardens will give you a feel for old times.

neighborhood_overview:
Dogpatch is one of the sunniest, walkable and connected neighborhoods in San Francisco. This is a place where tree-lined streets and classic Victorians mingle with historic warehouses and the heritage of industry and shipbuilding.

If Dogpatch were a kingdom in Game of Thrones, it would most closely resemble Dorne. Separated from the rest of SF and free spirited like the cities of Essos, itâ€™s industrial past has been turned to its advantage with some of the most innovative & eco-friendly industrial condos in the city and like Dorne, is home to some great wine shops & eateries, an eclectic collections of galleries and working art studios. The neighborhood is dotted with small parks, playgrounds, walking/running trails & biggest bouldering gym in the U.S. (if youâ€™re into rock climbing) Crane Cove Park, 7-acre urban park, (part of the re-development of Pier 70)mis a short walk and offers some spectacular walking trails and views of the bay and East Bay HIlls..

host_about:
Greetings!

My name is Warren C. Lathe III, I go by Trey (a nickname, means "3" :). I am a career biologist (molecular genetics) though currently, I'm writing, teaching and other things (like Airbnb!).Â 

My partner in crime since 1996, and legal husband since 2008, is Guy and we have two school-age (middle and high schools) children (the picture here was 8 years ago :D). Guy is an English as a Second Language teacher by training and career, but now manages properties.

We have a long and deep connection to San Francisco. Guy is a Berryessa. The Berryessa's settled San Francisco and the bay in the 1770s coming with the De Anza party in 1776. His GGrandfather was Jose de los Santos Berryessa. Â Guy's parents were married and lived in this city during the '40s (while his father fought in the Pacific theater). My own parents moved to the Bay Area in the 80's. Guy and I both moved into this home in 1997. San Francisco had been our dream city for its acceptance, tolerance, family heritageÂ and its beauty. It has been our permanentÂ home since (though my job took us to Â Heidelberg Germany for four years ('99-'03) and DC for two ('12-'14).

Other than science and education, I'm a history, gardening, cooking and travel fanatic :). Guy loves traveling and design. Our eldest is all about acting, singing, make-up, friends, family and the indoors. Our younger is all about dance (Jazz, Modern, HipHop), building things, friends and the outdoors.

Between us we speak passable Korean (me), Swedish (Guy), German (both) and a bit of Spanish (Guy).

Looking forward to meeting you!

Down the hill, take Folsom street to Precita Park. Itâ€™s a great neighborhood/family park. Thereâ€™s a nice corner grocery at the corner of Folsom and Precita. And at the other end of the park at Alabama street is Precita Park Cafeâ€¦a great place for breakfast, lunch or dinner.

Thereâ€™s a Safeway on Mission Street nearby or Grocery Outlet on South Van Ness, also close by.

On the other side of the hill (a very nice walk!) youâ€™ll find Cortland Street with great restaurants, bars, and another grocery store. Vino Rosso Enoteca, Vega and Bernal Star are all highly recommended.

description:

A quiet and comfortable home suited for any family, traveling worker or friends visiting San Francisco. We hope you enjoy!
neighborhood_overview:
The Potrero Hill district is one of the most unique neighborhoods in San Francisco and has gone through several changes from working class to the newer family oriented direction since the 1990's

Potrero Hill is one of the sunniest neighborhoods in San Francisco. It is insulated from our famous fog and chill from the ocean and gives some of the most spectacular views of downtown and the bay bridge. If you are up for a few hills it can be a great walking experience and the ever growing "hub" of 18th street is always a great place to start a day.

One of the best parts of Potrero Hill is that it is a neighborhood further from the "hustle and bustle" so it has a quiet and sleepy feel but you are never more than a few minutes from the fray.
host_about:

We are big movie buffs, foodies to our core and can't live without some good coffee :) 

Giving new people an opportunity to experience San Francisco is what we hope to do as hosts.  One of us was born in San Francisco (the other in Miami) and think there are a ton of fantastic things to experience here while on your stay either for work or fun :)

We hope that people have a fun and relaxing stay but mostly are happy!

neighborhood_overview:
Bernal Heights is a cute and friendly neighborhood with wonderful diversity and particular popularity with families. It is safe and lower density than downtown. It feels like a little town within San Francisco in part due to the offerings on Cortland Ave which can provide all the dining, cafe, shopping, grocery, banking, bar/brewery, and library essentials within walking distance of virtually all of our neighborhood.

Bernal Hill itself is an awesome park and offers towering views of the city with impressive vistas of the city, the bay/Oakland, and mountains north, east, and south of the city.

Holly Park is a bird watchers paradise and includes baseball diamond, playgrounds, and picnic areas.

The neighborhood is imminently walkable with beautiful homes, hidden gardens, and secret staircases everywhere! Alemany farmers market, one of California's oldest farmers markets, is open Saturdays and the same site hosts flea markets on Sundays.

description:
Entire Russian Hill flat centrally located to all the major sites! This is a typical San Francisco "Victorian" style apartment build over 100yrs ago with, but with an updated kitchen and bathrooms.

neighborhood_overview:
There are so many hidden gems in Russian Hill.

For starters, it is one of San Francisco's 49 hills, and one of its original "Seven Hills". The neighborhood's name goes back to the Gold Rush era, when settlers discovered a small Russian cemetery at the top of the hill. Russian naval and merchant ships frequently visited San Francisco throughout the 19th century beginning in 1806, back when it was called Yerba Buena and was part of the Spanish/Mexican empire. The cemetery has since been removed, but the name remains to this day.

With so much history in the area, you'll discover something fun and unique around every corner.

Some of my favorites are (in no particular order):

â€¢ George Sterling Park - named after the famous SF poet who penned "City By The Sea", this hilltop park host a tennis court that offers some hidden views of the Bay and of the Golden Gate Bridge. It's just around the corner; come during Sunset.

â€¢ Macondray Lane

There are many sites to see within walking distance of my apartment, so bring a good pair of shoes. Bernal Heights' Cortland Avenue offers a varied selection of casual but excellen

Experience central location in San Francisco in Sunny N. Bernal Heights, this beautifully remodeled century-old Victorian boasts New Kitchen and modern creature comforts such as Smart TVs, USB plugs, High-Speed WIFI Internet, and Smart Keypad locks in every room.

neighborhood_overview:
Beautiful weather, good food, and wonderful people in the community let you experience the old, kinder San Francisco.

Nestled in the heart of N. Bernal Heights, quiet and quaint with a feel of a Parisian neighborhood. Just downstairs, enjoy fun conversations and morning coffee at Charlie's Cafe. Enjoy authentic Mexican Gourmet Food
and try a French Michelin Star Restaurant across the street.

Harvest Hill Market is steps away when you get the munchies or need some milk and eggs.

Take a stroll or picnic at Precita Park, with a fantastic playground for young children.

Check out all the beautiful murals around the neighborhood, or take a class from Precita Eyes to learn how to make incredible artwork of your own.

Take a short, heart-pumping, verticle hike up Folsom Street to Bernal Heights Peak to experience breathtaking views of San Francisco and the Bay.
